{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "First, data cleaning aims to improve a machine learning model's overall performance by removing \"bad\" training data.",
    "These \"bad\" instances arise due to disparate non-malicious causes including human/algorithmic labeling error, non-representative instances, noisy features, missing features, etc.",
    "(Krishnan et al., 2016; Liu et al., 2018; Krishnan & Wu, 2019).",
    "Intuitively, \"bad\" training instances are generally anomalous, and their features clash with the feature distribution of typical \"clean\" data (Wojnowicz et al., 2016).",
    "In practice, overparameterized neural networks commonly memorize these \"bad\" instances to achieve zero training loss (Hara et al., 2019; Feldman & Zhang, 2020; Pruthi et al., 2020; Thimonier et al., 2022)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "(Krishnan et al., 2016; Liu et al., 2018; Krishnan & Wu, 2019).",
